Column Comment.0: SUPPORT FACILITY SUBTYPE: check constraint value that is used to maintain therelationship between SUPPORT FACILITY and its various sub-types. In this table,may only be SF_OTHER.
Column Comment.1: SUPPORT FACILITY IDENTIFIER: Unique identifier for the support facility. A supportfacility provides operational support for activities. These facilities may include roads,transmission towers, airstrips, vessels, docks and so on. Sub tyes are used tomaintain integration with the rest of the model.
Column Comment.2: ACTIVATION FREQUENCY DESCRIPTION: Narrative description of the frequencyor method that is used to activate the system.
Column Comment.3: ACTIVATION TONE DESCRIPTION: A narrative description of the activation tonesused by the facility.
Column Comment.4: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether this row of data is currently eitheractive / valid (Y) or inactive / invalid (N).
Column Comment.5: AIRSPACE DESCRIPTION: A short narrative description about the airspace, oftenthe identify of the control tower and its communication frequency.
Column Comment.6: ALTITUDE: The altitude or elevation of the facility.
Column Comment.8: APPROACH DIRECTION: the direction of approach for the facility, often expressedas a direction pair (s - n) or as a relative location (approach from tower).
Column Comment.9: AREA ID: Unique identifier for any named area such as a country, province, projectarea, area of interest, offshore area, district etc.
Column Comment.10: AREA SIZE: the total area of the heliport or helipad facility.
Column Comment.12: AREA TYPE: Unique identifier for the type of area, such as country, state, AOI etc.
Column Comment.13: COMMUNICATION FREQUENCY: the frequency to be used for comunication,expressed in MHz. Units of measure are not provided, as the frequuencies arealways in MHz.
Column Comment.14: COMMUNICATION FREQUENCY DESCRIPTION: a short narrative description ofthe communication frequency, such as where it should be obtained from or how toget it. In some cases, the communcation frequency may be provided as well.
Column Comment.15: DEPARTURE DIRECTION: the direction of departure from the facility, oftenexpressed as a direction pair (s - n) or as a relative location (approach from tower).
Column Comment.16: EFFECTIVE DATE: The date that the data in this row first came into effect.
Column Comment.17: EXPIRY DATE: The date that the data in this row was no longer active or in effect.
Column Comment.18: FUEL AVAILABILITY DESC: A narrative description about the availability of fuel onthe site.
Column Comment.19: FACILITY LANDING CODE: The code for the helipad or heliport or airstrip or airport.This column is not validated by a seperate reference table at this time, as this tableshould probably be considered the reference table for all landing facilities (ie this is acomplex reference list).
Column Comment.20: SUPPORT FACILITY LANDING FACILITY or HELIPORT TYPE: The type of landingfacility, such as airstrip or heliport. May be a helipad (A prepared area designatedand used for takeoff and landing of helicopters. (Includes touchdown or hover point.)) or a heliport (A facility designated for operating, basing, servicing, and maintaininghelicopters).
Column Comment.21: LIGHTING AVAILABLE INDICATOR: a Y/N flag indicating whether lighting isavailable on the landing site.
Column Comment.22: LIGHTING CYCLE DESCRIPTION: A narrative description of the kind of lightingcycle in use at the facility, such as: 5th between 5, rotating light on 10 feet, break 3thlight on.
Column Comment.23: LIGHTING DESCRIPTION: Narrative description of the lighting available on thefacility.
Column Comment.24: MAXIMUM ALLOWABLE MASS: The maximum mass or weight that this helport orhelipad is able to support.
Column Comment.25: MAXIMUM ALLOWABLE MASS DESCRIPTION: a narrative description about theallowable mass for the facility.
Column Comment.27: PERMANENT OBSTACLE DESCRIPTION: narrative comments about permanentobstacles, such as buildings, trees, powerlines etc.
Column Comment.28: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL should be created.
Column Comment.29: RADIO CALL NAME: The call name by which the facility is known for radiocommunications.
Column Comment.30: RADIO CHANNEL: the channel to tune to in order to recieve radio transmissionsfrom the facility.
Column Comment.31: REMARK: Narrative remarks relating to this row of data.
Column Comment.32: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.33: SPECIAL PROCEDURES DESCRIPTION: a narrative description of any specialprocedures in place, such as procedure to get permission to land, procdure forlanding etc.
Column Comment.34: SURFACE DESCRIPTION: Narrative description about the surface of the landingfield.
Column Comment.35: FACILITY SURFACE TYPE: A valid list of surface types for various support facility.May include concrete, asphalt, dirt, gravel, sand etc.
Column Comment.36: WEATHER INFORMATION DESCRIPTION: Narrative description abouat how toobtain weather information. If a service is used, you may use the FK to SF BASERVICE.
Column Comment.37: WINDCONE INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether there is a windcone on thelanding field.
Column Comment.38: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.39: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.40: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.41: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.42: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.43: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.44: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
